	<article class="post-31112 post type-post status-publish hentry tag-bribery-and-kickbacks tag-china tag-china-central-television tag-communist-party-of-china tag-corruption-institutional tag-economic-conditions-and-trends tag-gu-junshan tag-hu-jintao tag-li-peng tag-rui-chenggang tag-three-gorges-dam-china tag-tianjin-china tag-transparency-international tag-wang-qishan tag-wen-jiabao tag-xi-jinping tag-xu-caihou tag-zhou-yongkang per-gu-junshan per-hu-jintao per-li-peng per-rui-chenggang per-wang-qishan per-wen-jiabao per-xi-jinping per-xu-caihou per-zhou-yongkang des-bribery-and-kickbacks des-corruption-institutional des-economic-conditions-and-trends des-three-gorges-dam-china org-china-central-television org-communist-party-of-china org-transparency-international geo-china geo-tianjin-china news_keywords-bribery-and-kickbacks news_keywords-china news_keywords-china-central-television news_keywords-communist-party-of-china news_keywords-corruption news_keywords-economy news_keywords-gu-junshan news_keywords-hu-jintao news_keywords-li-peng news_keywords-rui-chenggang news_keywords-three-gorges-dam news_keywords-tianjin-china-2 news_keywords-transparency-international news_keywords-wang-qishan news_keywords-wen-jiabao news_keywords-xi-jinping news_keywords-xu-caihou news_keywords-zhou-yongkang" id="post-31112">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Q. and A.: Liao Ran on the Trial of Zhou Yongkang and China&#8217;s New Gang of Four</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Didi Kirsten Tatlow			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-05-27T22:00:36+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 27, 2015 6:00 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 27, 2015 6:00 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/22/world/21sino-liao02/21sino-liao02-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/22/world/21sino-liao02/21sino-liao02-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/22/world/21sino-liao02/21sino-liao02-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003696346" width="592" height="395" alt="Zhou Yongkang, former security chief, at the Great Hall of the People in Beijing on Oct. 22, 2007. He is accused of bribery, abuse of power and leaking state secrets."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Zhou Yongkang, former security chief, at the Great Hall of the People in Beijing on Oct. 22, 2007. He is accused of bribery, abuse of power and leaking state secrets.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Feng Li/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/05/27/q-and-a-liao-ran-on-the-trial-of-zhou-yongkang-and-chinas-new-gang-of-four/" data-title="Q. and A.: Liao Ran on the Trial of Zhou Yongkang and China&#8217;s New Gang of Four" data-description="Liao Ran, a corruption analyst at Transparency International, discusses the fall of Zhou Yongkang, China&#039;s former security chief, and the consolidation of power by President Xi Jinping.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Later this year, Zhou Yongkang, China&#8217;s former security chief, is expected <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/03/world/asia/china-zhou-yongkang-communist-party-faces-corruption-trial.html">to appear in court</a> in the country&#8217;s <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/06/world/asia/zhou-yongkang-china-arrests-former-security-chief.html">most significant political trial</a> since that of the Maoist Gang of Four in 1981. This time the action revolves around a new Gang of Four, says Liao Ran, an anticorruption advocate who has followed Mr. Zhou&#8217;s career closely.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/20/blogs/21sino-liao/20sino-liao-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/20/blogs/21sino-liao/20sino-liao-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/20/blogs/21sino-liao/20sino-liao-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003692089" width="190" height="281" alt="Liao Ran, of Transparency International."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="281"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Liao Ran, of Transparency International.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Didi Kirsten Tatlow/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Liao believes that the trial of Mr. Zhou for <a href="//news.xinhuanet.com/legal/2015-04/03/c_1114858961.htm">bribery, abuse of power and revealing state secrets</a> may take place after the annual summer gathering of Communist Party leaders at the seaside resort of Beidaihe, as leaders must reach final agreement on how to handle the case. It will involve the arraignment of a figure with once-untouchable status â Mr. Zhou, 72, was a member of the party Politburo&#8217;s Standing Committee, the inner circle of power.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What happened?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Liao, 55, is a senior program officer in Germany with Transparency International, an anticorruption organization, who has studied graft in China for 15 years as it ballooned alongside the economy then came under attack in 2013 from President Xi Jinping, whose corruption-fighting campaign upended the careers of thousands of senior officials. In an interview he discussed Mr. Xi&#8217;s goals, the new &#8216;Gang of Four,&#8217; and what makes top officials vulnerable. Here are edited excerpts:</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why does one corrupt official fall and not another?</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-31112"></span></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It hinges on a triangle of factors. The first is politics. The second is vested economic interests. The third is corruption. Mr. Xi was very clever to use corruption as the main way to attack his enemies, because almost everyone is corrupt, so everyone is vulnerable. You can&#8217;t arrest a billion people. But if you are vulnerable on all three points, then you and your family may fall.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Corruption and politics have always gone hand in hand in China, but vested economic interests are the new, key element here. Mr. Xi is determined to break these to reform China&#8217;s economy and create new growth.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How does the triangle work?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Take powerful families such as <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/10/26/business/global/family-of-wen-jiabao-holds-a-hidden-fortune-in-china.html">the Wens</a> [the family of former Premier Wen Jiabao] and the Lis [the family of an earlier premier, Li Peng]. Both are corrupt, but Wen&#8217;s family is not truly in danger as he is politically too tame. He is merely guilty of greed. He has no major vested interests to speak of.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Lis are under pressure. They are big in energy. The Three Gorges Dam project, which Mr. Li oversaw, is a cesspool of corruption, mostly through procurement contracts, and the Central Discipline Inspection Commission [China&#8217;s anticorruption authority] knows it. Mr. Li&#8217;s family has faced some danger. But, ultimately, probably they will not fall, because Li does not offend politically too much either.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Zhou Yongkang is different. He is corrupt. His fall is a huge opportunity to smash vested interests in oil. [Mr. Zhou had a long career as an oil official.] But the real reason is politics. Xi Jinping is intent on economic reform, and that made him dangerous to the powerful vested interests that run China, such as Mr. Zhou. They wanted to get rid of him and plotted to do so.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>[Unlike Mr. Zhou, who was charged last month with <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/03/world/asia/china-zhou-yongkang-communist-party-faces-corruption-trial.html">bribery, abuse of power and disclosing state secrets</a>, Mr. Li and Mr. Wen have not been charged with any crimes. Both families have denied allegations of wrongdoing.]</em></p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>So you believe the rumors of a coup plot that circulated in late 2012 and early 2013, as Mr. Xi was assuming his positions as general secretary of the party and president?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I believe it&#8217;s true. By that point, the military was an independent kingdom. Neither Mr. Hu [Hu Jintao, the former head of the army, the president and the party general secretary, all positions Mr. Xi holds today] nor Mr. Wen could control it during their 10 years in power. Mr. Zhou ran the People&#8217;s Armed Police, he ran the Public Security Bureau and State Security. Together with Gen. Xu Caihou [former vice chairman of the Central Military Commission, who was investigated for corruption and died of cancer last March] and others he controlled the military. So when Mr. Xi came to power, this is what he was facing. He had to break up a whole group of people.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Zhou was closely associated with <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/09/22/world/asia/bo-xilai-official-is-found-guilty-of-all-charges-and-given-life-term.html">Bo Xilai</a> [the former leader of Chongqing who was sentenced to life in prison in 2013 for corruption and abuse of power]. He wanted Mr. Bo to be his protector after he left power in 2012, to place him at the top, make him leader. He had other people helping him, such as <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/23/world/asia/china-opens-inquiry-into-ling-jihua-aide-to-hu-jintao.html">Ling Jihua</a> [a top aide to former President Hu who came under investigation in December]. The charges Mr. Zhou faces are very serious and include &#8220;nonparty political activities.&#8221; This relates to the belief he was organizing a coup to stop Mr. Xi and his planned economic changes.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How was the coup supposed to happen?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They didn&#8217;t want to get rid of Mr. Xi immediately, but after some years. They knew they couldn&#8217;t depose him instantly, with his rise to power underway.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are documents which state that Mr. Zhou and a group of people around him â Gen. Xu Caihou, Ling Jihua and Bo Xilai â formed the biggest political faction in the party since 1948. A new Gang of Four. Bigger than Lin Biao [the designated successor to Mao Zedong, who was accused of plotting a coup after he was killed in a plane crash in 1971], because that plot was proven to be untrue. So Mr. Xi used something from the era of [former leader] Deng Xiaoping to attack them. He accused them of intraparty fighting, which is not allowed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They are internal party documents. I don&#8217;t have them. My information comes from the inside.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After they&#8217;re all gone, Mr. Xi can do his reform. He can&#8217;t do it before, or he&#8217;ll just become another Mr. Hu.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What are the main interest groups that Mr. Xi felt needed to be broken up?<br />
</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Oil, coal and other energy; finance; CCTV [the state broadcaster]; and the military.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>How do you judge Mr. Xi&#8217;s success so far?</strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He has done very well. He knew all these officials were vulnerable on corruption, so he seized the moral high ground and mobilized support from the people, and the people supported him. A whole generation of the offspring of revolutionary leaders, the &#8220;red second generation,&#8221; people like himself, in government and in business, had felt neglected by the Gang of Four. Mr. Xi is their chief. What he made clear, together with Wang Qishan [the head of the anticorruption commission] is that anyone who kept going in their old ways after the <a href="//www.news.cn/english/special/18cpcnc/index.htm">18th Party Congress</a> [which elected him as party leader in 2012] would be a target. He is consolidating power.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>What is Xi Jinping&#8217;s goal? </strong></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Economic reform. Not political reform.</p>
	</div>
